<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06068019 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06068019 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; GAMBLING; GAME  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Little Lotto -- the latest effort to boost lottery sales -- was unveiledThursday by state officials who trumpeted it as the right gamble for peoplewho want shorter odds and an immediate jackpot payment of $500,000.;    &quot;Wehave been hearing for a long time that we needed a game with a big top prize-- something between Big Lotto and the top scratcher prizes,&quot; said spokeswomanJoanne McNabb.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LITTLE LOTTO GAME IMPROVES ODDS OF WINNING  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  California News.  </MEMO><TEXT>     The game has odds of winning the top prize at 1 in 3.2 million, comparedwith 1 in 23 million of winning the 6/53 jackpot. Big Lotto jackpots rangefrom $4 million to $69 million while scratcher top prizes run in the tens ofthousands.;    Beginning Sunday, lottery players will be able to buy $1tickets for Little Lotto. The winning Little Lotto numbers will be drawn everyTuesday and Friday.;    Little Lotto has only 39 numbers to choose from andthe $500,000 top prize is paid in one lump sum, rather than in installmentsover 20 years. If there are more than 20 top prize-winning tickets, however,they would split $10 million.;    Little Lotto is a fixed game likeScratchers, Decco and Topper, rather than a game such as Lotto 6/53 where thesize of the big jackpot depends on how many tickets are purchased.;    Besidesthe top prize, a player who matches five of six numbers wins $2,000; four ofsix numbers $50; and three of six numbers $3.;    Lottery officials increasedthe numbers from which lotto players can choose -- from 49 to 53 last summer.Complaints about the high odds in the 6/53 game, prompted the lottery staff toaccelerate plans to develop Little Lotto.;    Big Lotto game sales dropped 5percent or just under $100 million from $1.86 billion during fiscal year1988-'89 to $1.77 billion for fiscal year 1989-'90. This fiscal year theprojection is that sales will come in at about $1.5 billion.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  McClatchy News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Sacramento  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910308  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  320  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday March 8, 199100068019,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>